events.description: Arbogast has Eugenius elected Western Roman Emperor.
events.html: • 392 – Arbogast has Eugenius elected Western Roman Emperor.

events.description: Battle of Jengland: Erispoe defeats Charles the Bald near the Breton town of Jengland.
events.html: • 851 – Battle of Jengland: Erispoe defeats Charles the Bald near the Breton town of Jengland.

events.description: Battle of the Standard between Scotland and England.
events.html: • 1138 – Battle of the Standard between Scotland and England.[1]

events.description: Crusader–Fatimid wars: The fortress of Ascalon was surrendered by Fatimid Egypt to an army of crusaders, Templars, and Hospitallers led by King Baldwin III of Jerusalem.
events.html: • 1153 – Crusader–Fatimid wars: The fortress of Ascalon was surrendered by Fatimid Egypt to an army of crusaders, Templars, and Hospitallers led by King Baldwin III of Jerusalem.[2]

events.description: The Battle of Bosworth Field occurs; King Richard III of England's death in battle marks the end of the reigning Plantagenet dynasty and the beginning of the Tudors under Henry VII.
events.html: • 1485 – The Battle of Bosworth Field occurs; King Richard III of England's death in battle marks the end of the reigning Plantagenet dynasty and the beginning of the Tudors under Henry VII.[3]

events.description: Spanish archbishop Bartolomé Carranza is arrested for heresy.
events.html: • 1559 – Spanish archbishop Bartolomé Carranza is arrested for heresy.

events.description: Fettmilch Uprising: Jews are expelled from Frankfurt, Holy Roman Empire, following the plundering of the Judengasse.
events.html: • 1614 – Fettmilch Uprising: Jews are expelled from Frankfurt, Holy Roman Empire, following the plundering of the Judengasse.

events.description: Madras (now Chennai), India, is founded by the British East India Company on a sliver of land bought from local Nayak rulers.
events.html: • 1639 – Madras (now Chennai), India, is founded by the British East India Company on a sliver of land bought from local Nayak rulers.

events.description: Charles I raises his standard in Nottingham, which marks the beginning of the English Civil War.
events.html: • 1642 – Charles I raises his standard in Nottingham, which marks the beginning of the English Civil War.

events.description: Jacob Barsimson arrives in New Amsterdam. He is the first known Jewish immigrant to America.
events.html: • 1654 – Jacob Barsimson arrives in New Amsterdam. He is the first known Jewish immigrant to America.

events.description: Britain's Quebec Expedition loses eight ships and almost nine hundred soldiers, sailors and women to rocks at Pointe-aux-Anglais.
events.html: • 1711 – Britain's Quebec Expedition loses eight ships and almost nine hundred soldiers, sailors and women to rocks at Pointe-aux-Anglais.

events.description: Spanish troops land on Sardinia.
events.html: • 1717 – Spanish troops land on Sardinia.

events.description: James Cook names and lands on Possession Island, and claims the east coast of Australia for Britain as New South Wales.
events.html: • 1770 – James Cook names and lands on Possession Island, and claims the east coast of Australia for Britain as New South Wales.

events.description: British forces abandon the Siege of Fort Stanwix after hearing rumors of Continental Army reinforcements.
events.html: • 1777 – British forces abandon the Siege of Fort Stanwix after hearing rumors of Continental Army reinforcements.

events.description: James Cook's ship HMS Resolution returns to England (Cook having been killed on Hawaii during the voyage).
events.html: • 1780 – James Cook's ship HMS Resolution returns to England (Cook having been killed on Hawaii during the voyage).

events.description: The Haitian slave revolution begins in Saint-Domingue, Haiti.
events.html: • 1791 – The Haitian slave revolution begins in Saint-Domingue, Haiti.

events.description: French troops land at Kilcummin, County Mayo, Ireland to aid the rebellion.
events.html: • 1798 – French troops land at Kilcummin, County Mayo, Ireland to aid the rebellion.

events.description: José de La Mar becomes President of Peru.
events.html: • 1827 – José de La Mar becomes President of Peru.

events.description: The Second Federal Republic of Mexico is established.
events.html: • 1846 – The Second Federal Republic of Mexico is established.

events.description: Passaleão incident: João Maria Ferreira do Amaral, the governor of Portuguese Macau, is assassinated by a group of Chinese locals, triggering a military confrontation between China and Portugal at the Battle of Passaleão three days after.
events.html: • 1849 – Passaleão incident: João Maria Ferreira do Amaral, the governor of Portuguese Macau, is assassinated by a group of Chinese locals, triggering a military confrontation between China and Portugal at the Battle of Passaleão three days after.[4]

events.description: The first America's Cup is won by the yacht America.
events.html: • 1851 – The first America's Cup is won by the yacht America.

events.description: Twelve nations sign the First Geneva Convention, establishing the rules of protection of the victims of armed conflicts.
events.html: • 1864 – Twelve nations sign the First Geneva Convention, establishing the rules of protection of the victims of armed conflicts.[5]

events.description: The Treaty of Saint Petersburg between Japan and Russia is ratified, providing for the exchange of Sakhalin for the Kuril Islands.
events.html: • 1875 – The Treaty of Saint Petersburg between Japan and Russia is ratified, providing for the exchange of Sakhalin for the Kuril Islands.

events.description: Mahatma Gandhi forms the Natal Indian Congress (NIC) in order to fight discrimination against Indian traders in Natal.
events.html: • 1894 – Mahatma Gandhi forms the Natal Indian Congress (NIC) in order to fight discrimination against Indian traders in Natal.

events.description: The Cadillac Motor Company is founded.
events.html: • 1902 – The Cadillac Motor Company is founded.

events.description: Theodore Roosevelt becomes the first President of the United States to make a public appearance in an automobile.
events.html: • 1902 – Theodore Roosevelt becomes the first President of the United States to make a public appearance in an automobile.

events.description: At least 6,000 people are killed by the magnitude 7.7 Kashgar earthquake in the Tien Shan mountains.
events.html: • 1902 – At least 6,000 people are killed by the magnitude 7.7 Kashgar earthquake in the Tien Shan mountains.[6]

events.description: Michael Collins, Commander-in-chief of the Irish Free State Army, is shot dead in an ambush during the Irish Civil War.
events.html: • 1922 – Michael Collins, Commander-in-chief of the Irish Free State Army, is shot dead in an ambush during the Irish Civil War.

events.description: Bill Woodfull of Australia becomes the only test cricket captain to twice regain The Ashes.
events.html: • 1934 – Bill Woodfull of Australia becomes the only test cricket captain to twice regain The Ashes.

events.description: World War II: German troops begin the Siege of Leningrad.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: German troops begin the Siege of Leningrad.

events.description: Brazil declares war on Germany, Japan and Italy.
events.html: • 1942 – Brazil declares war on Germany, Japan and Italy.

events.description: World War II: Holocaust of Kedros in Crete by German forces.
events.html: • 1944 – World War II: Holocaust of Kedros in Crete by German forces.

events.description: The Queen Charlotte earthquake is Canada's strongest since the 1700 Cascadia earthquake.
events.html: • 1949 – The Queen Charlotte earthquake is Canada's strongest since the 1700 Cascadia earthquake.

events.description: The penal colony on Devil's Island is permanently closed.
events.html: • 1953 – The penal colony on Devil's Island is permanently closed.

events.description: The OAS attempts to assassinate French president Charles de Gaulle.
events.html: • 1962 – The OAS attempts to assassinate French president Charles de Gaulle.

events.description: X-15 Flight 91 reaches the highest altitude of the X-15 program (107.96 km (67.08 mi) (354,200 feet)).
events.html: • 1963 – X-15 Flight 91 reaches the highest altitude of the X-15 program (107.96 km (67.08 mi) (354,200 feet)).

events.description: Juan Marichal, pitcher for the San Francisco Giants, strikes John Roseboro, catcher for the Los Angeles Dodgers, on the head with a bat, sparking a 14-minute brawl, one of the most violent on-field incidents in sports history.
events.html: • 1965 – Juan Marichal, pitcher for the San Francisco Giants, strikes John Roseboro, catcher for the Los Angeles Dodgers, on the head with a bat, sparking a 14-minute brawl, one of the most violent on-field incidents in sports history.[7]

events.description: Labor movements NFWA and AWOC merge to become the United Farm Workers Organizing Committee (UFWOC), the predecessor of the United Farm Workers.
events.html: • 1966 – Labor movements NFWA and AWOC merge to become the United Farm Workers Organizing Committee (UFWOC), the predecessor of the United Farm Workers.

events.description: Pope Paul VI arrives in Bogotá, Colombia. It is the first visit of a pope to Latin America.
events.html: • 1968 – Pope Paul VI arrives in Bogotá, Colombia. It is the first visit of a pope to Latin America.

events.description: J. Edgar Hoover and John Mitchell announce the arrest of 20 of the Camden 28.
events.html: • 1971 – J. Edgar Hoover and John Mitchell announce the arrest of 20 of the Camden 28.

events.description: Rhodesia is expelled by the IOC for its racist policies.
events.html: • 1972 – Rhodesia is expelled by the IOC for its racist policies.

events.description: The Congress of Chile votes in favour of a resolution condemning President Salvador Allende's government and demands that he resign or else be unseated through force and new elections.
events.html: • 1973 – The Congress of Chile votes in favour of a resolution condemning President Salvador Allende's government and demands that he resign or else be unseated through force and new elections.

events.description: Nicaraguan Revolution: The FSLN seizes the National Congress of Nicaragua, along with over a thousand hostages.
events.html: • 1978 – Nicaraguan Revolution: The FSLN seizes the National Congress of Nicaragua, along with over a thousand hostages.

events.description: The District of Columbia Voting Rights Amendment is passed by the U.S. Congress, although it is never ratified by a sufficient number of states.

events.description: Far Eastern Air Transport Flight 103 disintegrates in mid-air and crashes in Sanyi Township, Miaoli County, Taiwan. All 110 people on board are killed.
events.html: • 1981 – Far Eastern Air Transport Flight 103 disintegrates in mid-air and crashes in Sanyi Township, Miaoli County, Taiwan. All 110 people on board are killed.[8]

events.html: • 1985 – British Airtours Flight 28M suffers an engine fire during takeoff at Manchester Airport. The pilots abort but due to inefficient evacuation procedures 55 people are killed, mostly from smoke inhalation.

events.description: Nolan Ryan strikes out Rickey Henderson to become the first Major League Baseball pitcher to record 5,000 strikeouts.
events.html: • 1989 – Nolan Ryan strikes out Rickey Henderson to become the first Major League Baseball pitcher to record 5,000 strikeouts.

events.html: • 1991 – Iceland is the first nation in the world to recognize the independence of the Baltic states.

events.html: • 1992 – FBI sniper Lon Horiuchi shoots and kills Vicki Weaver during an 11-day siege at her home at Ruby Ridge, Idaho.

events.description: China Airlines Flight 642 crashes at Hong Kong International Airport, killing three people and injuring 208 more.
